1. Four symbols ≠ quantum

Having four possible symbols (A, T, C, G) doesn’t make something quantum.

A quantum system is defined by properties like:
	•	superposition
	•	entanglement
	•	wavefunction evolution

DNA bases are just chemical states. They don’t exist in superposition the way qubits do.

In information theory terms, DNA is simply a base-4 encoding system.

You could imagine a computer using:
	•	base-2 (binary)
	•	base-3
	•	base-4
	•	base-10

The base size doesn’t make it quantum — it just changes how information is represented.

